<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="generic diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Generic diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
Among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1869" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="tribe" tribe="Phaeogenini">Phaeogenini</taxonomicName>
genera, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wesmael" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognized by a combination of the following: unidentate, falciform mandible; epistomal suture distinct; basal flagellomeres slender and elongate (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Unpublished illustration of Heterischnus huardi (Provancher) lateral habitus and frontal view of head by Professor Masaaki Tokunaga or his assistants, commissioned by Dr. Henry Townes." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.85.67792.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/583736" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">1</figureCitation>
); scutellum moderately narrow, convex, and distinctly elevated above metanotum; areolet (cell 1-2Rs) of the fore wing is closed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Unpublished illustration of Heterischnus huardi (Provancher) lateral habitus and frontal view of head by Professor Masaaki Tokunaga or his assistants, commissioned by Dr. Henry Townes." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.85.67792.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/583736" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">1</figureCitation>
); hind coxa simple; thyridium wide. In some species, notably 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Provancher" baseAuthorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus huardi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huardi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus huardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Provancher), the clypeus is medially truncate with acute sublateral projections making such species instantly recognizable as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wesmael" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the ventral clypeal margin varies between the aforementioned morphology and being medially straight without acute sublateral projections. The majority of species tend toward the latter condition. Additionally, the tarsal claws of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="O.F.Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus pulex" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulex">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus pulex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
) are pectinate which is unique among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1869" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="tribe" tribe="Phaeogenini">Phaeogenini</taxonomicName>
, although the tarsal claws are simple in the remaining species.
</paragraph>
